<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Find Your Footing — HART Hub Recovery Tool</title>
<style>
  @import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Lora:ital,wght@0,400;0,500;1,400&family=DM+Sans:wght@300;400;500&display=swap');

  :root {
    --bg: #f5f0e8;
    --card: #fffdf8;
    --text: #2c2416;
    --muted: #8a7f6e;
    --accent: #6b8f71;
    --accent2: #c17f5a;
    --accent3: #5a7fa8;
    --border: #e2d9c8;
    --shadow: rgba(44,36,22,0.08);
    --crisis: rgba(193,127,90,0.07);
    --crisis-border: rgba(193,127,90,0.3);
  }

  * { box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0; padding: 0; }

  body {
    background: var(--bg);
    background-image: radial-gradient(ellipse at 20% 50%, rgba(107,143,113,0.07) 0%, transparent 60%),
                      radial-gradient(ellipse at 80% 20%, rgba(193,127,90,0.06) 0%, transparent 50%);
    min-height: 100vh;
    font-family: 'DM Sans', sans-serif;
    color: var(--text);
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    justify-content: center;
    padding: 24px 16px 48px;
  }

  .container { width: 100%; max-width: 660px; }

  .header {
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: 28px;
    opacity: 0;
    animation: fadeUp 0.6s ease forwards;
  }
  .header .leaf { font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 8px; display: block; }
  .header h1 { font-family: 'Lora', serif; font-size: 1.65rem; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: 0.01em; }
  .header p { font-size: 0.84rem; color: var(--muted); margin-top: 6px; font-weight: 300; }

  .card {
    background: var(--card);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 20px;
    padding: 36px 40px;
    box-shadow: 0 4px 24px var(--shadow), 0 1px 4px var(--shadow);
    opacity: 0;
    animation: fadeUp 0.5s ease 0.15s forwards;
  }

  .passage { display: none; }
  .passage.active { display: block; animation: fadeUp 0.35s ease forwards; }

  .prompt {
    font-family: 'Lora', serif;
    font-size: 1.13rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--text);
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .sub-prompt {
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin-bottom: 28px;
    font-weight: 300;
  }

  .choices { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }

  .choice {
    background: transparent;
    border: 1.5px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 12px;
    padding: 14px 18px;
    text-align: left;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-family: 'DM Sans', sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.91rem;
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.55;
    transition: all 0.2s ease;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .choice::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0; top: 0; bottom: 0;
    width: 3px;
    background: var(--accent);
    opacity: 0;
    transition: opacity 0.2s;
  }
  .choice:hover { border-color: var(--accent); background: rgba(107,143,113,0.05); transform: translateX(3px); }
  .choice:hover::before { opacity: 1; }

  .tool-card {
    border: 1.5px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 14px;
    padding: 20px 22px;
    margin-bottom: 14px;
    background: rgba(107,143,113,0.04);
  }
  .tool-card h3 {
    font-family: 'Lora', serif;
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--accent);
    margin-bottom: 7px;
  }
  .tool-card p { font-size: 0.87rem; color: var(--text); line-height: 1.65; }
  .tool-card .steps { margin-top: 10px; padding-left: 18px; }
  .tool-card .steps li { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.75; }

  .crisis-card { background: var(--crisis); border-color: var(--crisis-border); }
  .crisis-card h3 { color: var(--accent2); }

  .info-card { background: rgba(90,127,168,0.05); border-color: rgba(90,127,168,0.25); }
  .info-card h3 { color: var(--accent3); }

  .divider { border: none; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); margin: 22px 0; }

  .label {
    font-size: 0.74rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.09em;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin-bottom: 14px;
  }

  .anchor-phrase {
    margin-top: 20px;
    padding: 14px 18px;
    background: rgba(107,143,113,0.06);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0;
    font-family: 'Lora', serif;
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .back-btn {
    margin-top: 22px;
    background: none;
    border: none;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-family: 'DM Sans', sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.83rem;
    cursor: pointer;
    padding: 4px 0;
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 5px;
    transition: color 0.2s;
  }
  .back-btn:hover { color: var(--text); }

  .restart-btn {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-top: 20px;
    margin-right: 10px;
    padding: 11px 22px;
    border: 1.5px solid var(--accent);
    border-radius: 10px;
    background: none;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-family: 'DM Sans', sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    cursor: pointer;
    transition: all 0.2s;
  }
  .restart-btn:hover { background: var(--accent); color: white; }
  .btn-row { margin-top: 24px; display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 10px; align-items: center; }

  @keyframes fadeUp {
    from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(12px); }
    to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
  }

  @media (max-width: 480px) {
    .card { padding: 26px 22px; }
    .prompt { font-size: 1.05rem; }
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div class="container">
  <div class="header">
    <span class="leaf">🌿</span>
    <h1>Find Your Footing</h1>
    <p>HART Hub Core Addictions Programming · A guide to finding what you need, right now.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="card">

    <!-- START -->
    <div class="passage active" id="start">
      <p class="prompt">Hey. Good to have you here.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">This isn't a test — just a few honest questions to help point you toward something useful. Right now, how would you describe where you're at?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('overwhelmed')">Things feel heavy, out of control, or hard to manage</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('unsettled')">I'm okay-ish, but something feels off and I can't name it</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('craving')">I'm dealing with cravings or urges right now</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('emotions')">I'm having big emotions and don't know what to do with them</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('thoughts')">My thoughts are spinning or I keep looping over the same things</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('grief')">I'm grieving something — a loss, my past, what I've been through</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('shame')">I'm stuck in guilt, shame, or resentment</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('relationships')">I'm struggling with a relationship or communication</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('curious')">I want to understand what's happening in my brain or recovery</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('support')">I feel like I need to talk to someone</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('selfcare')">I want to take better care of myself but don't know where to start</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('relapse')">I'm worried about a lapse or relapse — or it already happened</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('vulnerability')">I want to open up more but vulnerability feels unsafe or hard</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('motivation')">I'm losing motivation for recovery and need to reconnect with my why</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('conversations')">I need help knowing what to say in hard conversations</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- OVERWHELMED -->
    <div class="passage" id="overwhelmed">
      <p class="prompt">That sounds really hard. You showed up anyway — that matters.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What's closest to what's happening right now?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('overwhelmed-body')">My body feels tense, wound up, or like I can't settle</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('overwhelmed-thoughts')">My thoughts are racing or I can't stop going over things</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('overwhelmed-numb')">I feel numb, flat, or disconnected — like I'm not really here</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('overwhelmed-crisis')">Honestly, I'm not sure I'm safe right now</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="overwhelmed-body">
      <p class="prompt">Your nervous system is working overtime. That's real — and you can work with it.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Grounding & Regulation</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Physiological Sigh</h3>
        <p>The fastest way to manually lower nervous system activation. Take a double inhale through the nose (breathe in, then sniff a little more), then a long slow exhale through your mouth. Repeat 2–3 times. Used by first responders and athletes under pressure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Box Breathing</h3>
        <p>Balances your nervous system and lowers heart rate.</p>
        <ul class="steps">
          <li>Inhale for <strong>4 counts</strong></li>
          <li>Hold for <strong>4 counts</strong></li>
          <li>Exhale for <strong>4 counts</strong></li>
          <li>Hold for <strong>4 counts</strong></li>
          <li>Repeat 4 times</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>5-4-3-2-1 Grounding</h3>
        <p>Brings your mind back to the present through your senses: name 5 things you can see, 4 you can touch, 3 you can hear, 2 you can smell, 1 you can taste.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Dropping Anchor</h3>
        <p>Press your feet firmly into the floor. Take one steady breath. Look around and name what you see. Say quietly: "I am in [room]. I am okay right now." Repeat until you feel more present.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"Each breath is a small decision to stay connected to myself."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('overwhelmed')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="overwhelmed-thoughts">
      <p class="prompt">A busy mind in recovery is doing its job — just maybe too well right now.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Regulation + Cognitive Skills</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Leaves on a Stream</h3>
        <p>Imagine a gently flowing stream. Each thought that shows up — place it on a leaf and watch it drift away without chasing it. You're the observer, not the thought.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>"I'm Having the Thought That…"</h3>
        <p>Instead of "I'm failing," try "I'm having the thought that I'm failing." This creates space between you and the thought. It reduces its authority without dismissing it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Worry Postponement</h3>
        <p>Write down what's on your mind — everything — and tell yourself: "I'll come back to this at [specific time]." The thoughts don't need to be solved right now. This gives your brain permission to set them down.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>4–7–8 Breathing</h3>
        <p>Inhale for <strong>4</strong>, hold for <strong>7</strong>, exhale slowly through your mouth for <strong>8</strong>. Extending the exhale releases tension and supports rest. Start with 2–3 rounds.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"You are not your thoughts. You are the awareness behind them."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('overwhelmed')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="overwhelmed-numb">
      <p class="prompt">Feeling disconnected is more common in recovery than people talk about. Your system is protecting you.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Grounding for Numbness & Dissociation</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Temperature Shift</h3>
        <p>Run cold water over your wrists or splash your face. Temperature change sends a fast signal to your nervous system that you're present and safe.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Feet on the Floor</h3>
        <p>Press your feet firmly into the ground. Move your toes. Say out loud: "I am in [room]. It is [date]. I am okay right now." Repeat until you feel more anchored.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Hand on Heart Breathing</h3>
        <p>Place one hand over your heart and breathe slowly. Feel the warmth and movement. This reconnects body and breath gently — useful during grief, shame, or feeling far away.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>When to Tell Someone</h3>
        <p>If this disconnected feeling happens often, bring it up with your counsellor or care team. Dissociation is a real and treatable response — not something to manage alone.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('overwhelmed')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="overwhelmed-crisis">
      <p class="prompt">Thank you for being honest about that. Please reach out to someone right now — you don't have to figure this out alone.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Crisis Resources</p>
      <div class="tool-card crisis-card">
        <h3>988 — Call or Text</h3>
        <p>Available 24/7. For mental health crises, substance use crises, or if you're not sure. A real person answers. You don't need to be in the worst moment of your life to call.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card crisis-card">
        <h3>Crisis Text Line</h3>
        <p>Text <strong>HOME to 741741</strong> if talking feels like too much. A real person will respond.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card crisis-card">
        <h3>ConnexOntario</h3>
        <p>Call <strong>1-866-531-2600</strong> — 24/7 mental health and addiction support across Ontario.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card crisis-card">
        <h3>Your Support Person</h3>
        <p>If you have a sponsor, counsellor, or someone in your corner — reach out now. You don't need the right words. "I'm struggling" is enough.</p>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('overwhelmed')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <!-- UNSETTLED -->
    <div class="passage" id="unsettled">
      <p class="prompt">That "something feels off" sense is worth paying attention to. Your body usually knows before your mind does.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What's closest to what you're noticing?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('unsettled-irritable')">I'm more irritable or on edge than usual</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('unsettled-flat')">I feel flat, unmotivated, or just empty</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('unsettled-lonely')">I feel alone in this, even around people</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('unsettled-halt')">I'm not sure — I might just need the basics (sleep, food, rest)</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="unsettled-irritable">
      <p class="prompt">Irritability in recovery is often stress or emotion that hasn't found a way out yet. It's information.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Coping Skills</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>HALT Check-In</h3>
        <p>Are you <strong>Hungry, Angry, Lonely, or Tired?</strong> These unmet basic needs are among the most common hidden relapse triggers. Addressing the underlying need often reduces intensity fast.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Name It to Tame It</h3>
        <p>Labelling an emotion ("I'm angry," "I feel disrespected") actually reduces its intensity in the brain. Irritability often has something underneath it — fear, hurt, or feeling unheard are common ones.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Physical Release</h3>
        <p>Walk, do push-ups, stretch hard, or shake your hands out. Irritability has energy behind it — give it somewhere to go. Even 5 minutes of movement helps.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('unsettled')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="unsettled-flat">
      <p class="prompt">Flatness and low motivation are really common in early and mid recovery. Your brain is literally rebuilding its reward system.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Psychoeducation + Coping</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Why You Feel Flat: The Dopamine Gap</h3>
        <p>Substance use flooded your brain with dopamine. Now that it's gone, your brain's natural reward system needs time to recalibrate. Feeling flat isn't a character flaw — it's neurological recovery. Research shows meaningful brain recovery happening at 3–12 months and beyond.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Behavioural Activation</h3>
        <p>Don't wait to feel motivated to act — act first, and the feeling often follows. Pick one small thing: make your bed, text someone, step outside for five minutes. Tiny actions rebuild momentum.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Pleasant Activity Scheduling</h3>
        <p>Choose one activity you used to enjoy — even if it doesn't feel enjoyable yet. Do it for just 5–10 minutes. Stop before you're tired. Consistency matters more than intensity. Your brain is slowly relearning pleasure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('unsettled')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="unsettled-lonely">
      <p class="prompt">Loneliness in recovery is one of the hardest things, and one of the least talked about. You're not weak for feeling it.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Connection + Support</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Reach Out — One Person, Right Now</h3>
        <p>Not a grand gesture. Just one text or call to someone safe. "Hey, thinking of you" counts. Connection doesn't have to be a conversation about recovery to matter.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Peer Support Groups</h3>
        <p>AA, NA, SMART Recovery, and many community groups exist specifically because this feeling is universal in recovery. <strong>aa.org</strong> · <strong>na.org</strong> · <strong>smartrecovery.org</strong></p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Hyperindependence in Recovery</h3>
        <p>"I can only rely on myself" is often a survival strategy, not a preference. If asking for help feels dangerous or shameful, that's worth exploring with a counsellor. Isolation increases relapse risk. Connection is protective.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('unsettled')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="unsettled-halt">
      <p class="prompt">Sometimes the most powerful thing you can do is check the basics first.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">HALT — Back to Basics</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The HALT Check</h3>
        <p>When irritable, restless, or discontent — pause and ask: am I <strong>Hungry? Angry? Lonely? Tired?</strong> These unmet basic needs are among the most common recovery disruptors.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Basic Self-Care Right Now</h3>
        <p>Eat something if you haven't. Drink water. Step outside for two minutes. Rest if you can. Sleep disruption is one of the most underestimated relapse risk factors — and often one of the most fixable.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Minimum Viable Routine</h3>
        <p>Pick 2–3 small daily anchors at the same time each day — a morning check-in, a steady meal, a quiet moment before bed. The brain prefers predictability. Even tiny routines reduce emotional volatility.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('unsettled')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CRAVING -->
    <div class="passage" id="craving">
      <p class="prompt">Cravings are hard — and completely normal. Your brain is doing what trained brains do.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What would be most helpful right now?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('craving-ride')">Help me get through this moment right now</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('craving-understand')">Help me understand why cravings happen</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('craving-plan')">I want to build a craving plan for next time</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('craving-talk')">I need to talk to someone before I make a decision</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="craving-ride">
      <p class="prompt">You can ride this out. A craving is a wave — it rises, peaks, and passes. Most urges last 20–30 minutes.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Immediate Craving Tools</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Urge Surfing</h3>
        <p>Don't fight the craving — observe it. Notice where you feel it in your body. Watch it rise, peak, and fall without acting on it. You're the surfer, not the wave.</p>
        <ul class="steps">
          <li>Say: "Here's an urge."</li>
          <li>Notice the body sensations — tension, heat, restlessness</li>
          <li>Name it: "This is craving."</li>
          <li>Take slow breaths — exhale longer than you inhale</li>
          <li>Watch it rise and fall without doing anything</li>
          <li>When it settles, choose one coping action</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>PAUSE → NOTICE → NAME → CHOOSE → ACT</h3>
        <p>Stop. Pay attention to your body. Say "I'm having the urge to…" Access your Wise Mind. Then choose one coping behaviour instead of acting on the urge.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>HALT Check</h3>
        <p>Right now: am I <strong>Hungry, Angry, Lonely, or Tired?</strong> Cravings often attach to unmet basic needs. Addressing the underlying need can reduce the intensity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Change Your Environment</h3>
        <p>Physically move if you can. Go outside, go to a different room, go somewhere public. Cravings are cued by environment — changing the scene changes the signal.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Delay 15 Minutes</h3>
        <p>Tell yourself: "I'll wait 15 minutes, then reassess." Use that time to ground or breathe. Urges reliably weaken without action.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"This urge will pass. I am not my urges."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('craving')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="craving-understand">
      <p class="prompt">Understanding the "why" is one of the most powerful tools in recovery.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Psychoeducation: Cravings</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>How Cravings Work: The Cue-Response Loop</h3>
        <p>Your brain learned to associate certain cues — people, places, emotions, times of day — with substance use. When it encounters those cues, it fires off a powerful "wanting" signal. This isn't weakness; it's learned neurological wiring. It can be unlearned through new experience.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Dopamine Anticipation</h3>
        <p>Your brain releases dopamine when it anticipates the substance — not just when you use. So a craving is your anticipatory reward system activating. Recognizing this creates distance: "My brain is predicting a reward. That's not the same as a need."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Cognitive Distortions During Cravings</h3>
        <p>Thoughts like "just once," "I can handle it," or "I deserve this" are automatic mental shortcuts the brain learned for fast relief. They feel true but don't reflect the full picture. Slow the moment down enough to see the whole story.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What Weakens the Cue-Response Link</h3>
        <p>Every time you ride out a craving without acting on it, you're weakening the brain's learned pathway. It takes time — but the pathway genuinely does fade. This is neuroplasticity working for you.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('craving')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="craving-plan">
      <p class="prompt">Having a craving plan before the wave hits makes a real difference.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Craving Plan Framework</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Know Your Triggers</h3>
        <p><strong>Internal:</strong> stress, anxiety, loneliness, exhaustion, rumination, physical sensations. <strong>External:</strong> certain people, places, times of day, objects, conflict. Write yours down somewhere accessible.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Build Your Coping Menu</h3>
        <p>Before a craving hits, choose 3–5 tools across categories: <strong>Body</strong> (breathing, movement, cold water), <strong>Mind</strong> (grounding, thought defusion), <strong>Heart</strong> (calling someone, journaling). Having options matters — no single tool works every time.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Identify Your Support Person</h3>
        <p>Decide now — not in the middle of a craving — who you can contact when urges are high. A sponsor, peer, counsellor, or trusted person. Even a short call or text can shift everything.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Values Reminder</h3>
        <p>Choose one value to return to when cravings show up. Ask: "Which choice moves me toward the life I want?" You're not deciding forever — just the next right direction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('craving')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="craving-talk">
      <p class="prompt">Reaching out in this moment is one of the strongest things you can do.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Support + Referral</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Call Your Sponsor or Support Person</h3>
        <p>A two-minute call in a high-craving moment can shift everything. You don't need a reason beyond "I needed to hear a voice."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>ConnexOntario</h3>
        <p>Call <strong>1-866-531-2600</strong> — free, confidential, 24/7. They can connect you to local services or just talk through what you're experiencing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card crisis-card">
        <h3>If It Feels Urgent</h3>
        <p>Text or call <strong>988</strong>. Substance use crises count. You deserve support right now.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('craving')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- EMOTIONS -->
    <div class="passage" id="emotions">
      <p class="prompt">Emotions are signals, not problems. Let's figure out what yours might be trying to say.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What's closest to what you're experiencing?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('emotions-big')">My emotions feel too big — overwhelming or flooding</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('emotions-name')">I feel something but I can't name it or find the words</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('emotions-express')">I know what I feel but I don't know what to do with it</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('emotions-anger')">I keep getting angry or reactive and I don't want to</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="emotions-big">
      <p class="prompt">When emotions flood, your Window of Tolerance has been exceeded. This is manageable.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Emotional Regulation</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Temperature: Cold Water</h3>
        <p>Splash cold water on your face or hold something very cold. This rapidly reduces emotional intensity — one of the fastest physiological resets available. <em>Check with your nurse first if you have heart or circulation conditions.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Paced Breathing</h3>
        <p>Inhale for 4 counts, exhale slowly for 6 counts. Repeat 2–3 minutes. The extended exhale activates the parasympathetic nervous system and brings emotional intensity down.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The 6/10 Rule</h3>
        <p>If your distress is above a 6/10, pause and ground first. You don't need to process big emotions at full intensity. Work in smaller, safer amounts. Presence — not overwhelm — is the goal.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Emotions Come in Waves</h3>
        <p>Emotions are not permanent states. Even strong ones usually peak and pass within minutes when not fought or avoided. Staying present without escaping — that's how emotions move through instead of getting stuck.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"I can stay with this feeling. It will rise and fall."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('emotions')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="emotions-name">
      <p class="prompt">Not being able to name a feeling is very common — especially in recovery. Your body felt it before your mind has words.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Identifying Emotions</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Start with Your Body</h3>
        <p>Forget the word for now. Where do you feel something in your body? <strong>Tight chest</strong> → possibly anxiety, fear, or anger. <strong>Heavy chest</strong> → possibly sadness or grief. <strong>Heat in face</strong> → possibly anger or shame. <strong>Stomach drop</strong> → possibly fear. <strong>Numbness</strong> → possibly overwhelm or shutdown.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Emotion Buckets</h3>
        <p>If you can't name it specifically, pick a bucket: <strong>ANGER</strong> · <strong>SADNESS</strong> · <strong>FEAR</strong> · <strong>SHAME</strong> · <strong>NUMB/SHUT DOWN</strong> · <strong>CONFUSED</strong> · <strong>JOY/CALM</strong> · <strong>I DON'T KNOW.</strong> Not knowing is still progress.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Primary vs Secondary Emotions</h3>
        <p>What you feel on the surface is often a secondary emotion — anger, irritability, withdrawal. Underneath is usually a primary emotion — hurt, fear, shame, sadness. Ask: "If I wasn't angry, what would I be feeling?" That's usually where the real need lives.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('emotions')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="emotions-express">
      <p class="prompt">Emotions don't disappear when ignored. They build pressure. Expression releases it safely.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Safe Emotional Expression</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Emotion → Need → Expression</h3>
        <p>Emotions point to needs. Try: "I feel ___ → I need ___ → I can express it by ___." Example: "I feel lonely → I need connection → I can ask for support." Expressing the need reduces the pressure of the emotion.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Safe Expression Statements</h3>
        <p>Try: "I feel ___ because ___. I need ___. What helps me is ___." Name the feeling, name the cause without blame, name the need. This isn't venting — it's communication.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Non-Verbal Expression</h3>
        <p>Writing, art, music, movement — emotions don't always need words. Try drawing your emotion as a colour, shape, or weather pattern. Expression is release, not performance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Journaling Prompt</h3>
        <p>Write for 5 minutes without stopping: "Right now my body feels… The emotion underneath might be… What I need most is…" Don't edit. Just let it out.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('emotions')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="emotions-anger">
      <p class="prompt">Anger in recovery makes sense. It often protects something more vulnerable underneath.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Working with Anger</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What's Underneath?</h3>
        <p>Anger is often a secondary emotion. Ask: "If I wasn't angry, what would I be feeling?" Common answers: hurt, fear, shame, disappointment, powerlessness. The primary emotion is where the real need lives.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The STOP Skill</h3>
        <p><strong>S</strong> — Stop. Don't react yet. <strong>T</strong> — Take a breath. <strong>O</strong> — Observe what's happening inside and around you. <strong>P</strong> — Proceed mindfully. Choose your next step with care.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Physical Release First</h3>
        <p>Walk fast, do push-ups, stretch aggressively. Anger has energy behind it — give it a physical outlet before trying to have the conversation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Assertive Expression</h3>
        <p>Instead of reacting: "I feel frustrated when ___ because ___. I need ___." Speaking from "I" reduces defensiveness and actually gets heard more effectively.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('emotions')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- THOUGHTS -->
    <div class="passage" id="thoughts">
      <p class="prompt">The mind can become a very loud place in recovery. Let's slow this down.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What's closest to what's happening in your thinking?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('thoughts-rumination')">I keep looping over the same thoughts and can't stop</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('thoughts-selftalk')">My inner voice is really harsh or critical right now</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('thoughts-distortions')">My thinking feels distorted — catastrophizing, all-or-nothing</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('thoughts-wisemind')">I know what I should do but I can't seem to access it</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="thoughts-rumination">
      <p class="prompt">Rumination is like a rocking chair — it feels like doing something but doesn't move you anywhere.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Breaking the Loop</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Control Check</h3>
        <p>Ask: "Is this something I can actually influence or change right now?" If yes — take one small action step. If no — move to grounding or defusion. Rumination pretends it's problem-solving. It usually isn't.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Leaves on a Stream</h3>
        <p>Imagine a gently flowing stream. Place each repeating thought on a leaf and watch it drift away without chasing it. You're not forcing thoughts away — you're letting them pass.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>5-4-3-2-1 Grounding</h3>
        <p>Bring your attention back through your senses: 5 things you see, 4 you touch, 3 you hear, 2 you smell, 1 you taste. Rumination lives in the past or future — your senses only exist right now.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Values Redirect</h3>
        <p>When you notice the loop: ask "What matters most to me right now?" This shifts focus from the spinning thought to your actual direction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('thoughts')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="thoughts-selftalk">
      <p class="prompt">The way you talk to yourself matters — especially when things are hard.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Managing Self-Talk</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>"I'm Having the Thought That…"</h3>
        <p>Instead of "I'm a failure," try "I'm having the thought that I'm a failure." This creates space between you and the thought. It reduces the thought's authority without dismissing it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The "Would I Say This to Someone I Care About?" Test</h3>
        <p>Take the thought. Would you say it to a friend in pain? If no — it's not fair to say to yourself either. What would the kinder, more accurate version be?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Rewriting Harsh Self-Talk</h3>
        <p>Not toxic positivity — just accuracy. "I always screw up" → "I make mistakes, but I'm learning." "I can't handle this" → "This is hard, and I can get through it one step at a time."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Narrator Swap</h3>
        <p>Imagine the same thought spoken by a calm therapist, a wise friend, or an older version of yourself who's been through recovery. How would they say it? What would they add?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('thoughts')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="thoughts-distortions">
      <p class="prompt">Cognitive distortions aren't character flaws — they're mind habits. The brain filling in gaps too confidently.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Common Thinking Traps</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Patterns to Recognize</h3>
        <p><strong>Catastrophizing:</strong> jumping to worst-case. <strong>All-or-nothing:</strong> no middle ground. <strong>Mind reading:</strong> assuming what others think. <strong>Emotional reasoning:</strong> "I feel like a failure, so I must be." <strong>Should statements:</strong> rigid rules that create shame. <strong>Personalization:</strong> blaming yourself for things outside your control.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Thought Record — 4 Steps</h3>
        <p><strong>1.</strong> Write the thought exactly. <strong>2.</strong> Name the pattern. <strong>3.</strong> Rewrite it in a fair, balanced, honest way — as you'd say to a friend. <strong>4.</strong> Notice: did the feeling shift even slightly?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Wise Mind Response</h3>
        <p>Ask: "If I play the tape forward, what usually happens?" "What part of me is speaking right now?" "What does my Wise Mind already know is true?" You're not arguing with the thought — you're widening the frame.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('thoughts')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="thoughts-wisemind">
      <p class="prompt">Wise Mind is the place where your heart and head agree — where you know what's right and can feel it too.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Accessing Wise Mind</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>The Three Mind States</h3>
        <p><strong>Emotion Mind:</strong> feelings drive decisions — fast, reactive, intense. <strong>Rational Mind:</strong> logic leads, disconnected from feeling. <strong>Wise Mind:</strong> the balance point — you notice feelings AND think clearly. It often feels like clarity: "This is the next right step."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>How to Access Wise Mind — Right Now</h3>
        <ul class="steps">
          <li>Put both feet flat on the floor</li>
          <li>Take one slow breath in and out</li>
          <li>Feel your chest move</li>
          <li>Ask: "What feels true right now?"</li>
          <li>Listen for the calm answer, not the loud one</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="margin-top:8px; font-size:0.85rem; color:var(--muted);">The calm answer is usually Wise Mind.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Wise Mind Is a Skill, Not a Mood</h3>
        <p>You may not be able to force it when emotions are very high. The goal: bring your intensity down first through breathing or grounding, then ask the question.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('thoughts')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- GRIEF -->
    <div class="passage" id="grief">
      <p class="prompt">Grief in recovery is real, valid, and often unspoken. You're not just grieving a substance — you're grieving what it did for you.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What feels closest to what you're carrying right now?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('grief-addiction')">I'm grieving my relationship with addiction itself</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('grief-losses')">I'm grieving time, relationships, or opportunities lost</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('grief-identity')">I don't know who I am anymore — my identity feels lost</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('grief-selfcare')">I'm grieving and I don't know how to take care of myself through it</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="grief-addiction">
      <p class="prompt">Missing something that also harmed you is one of the most confusing, least-talked-about parts of recovery. You're not alone in this.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Grief Over Addiction</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Why Addiction Feels Like a Loss</h3>
        <p>Addiction may have functioned like a relationship — providing comfort, escape, relief, routine, or connection. When recovery begins, the brain experiences something similar to loss. You're not grieving the substance itself — you're grieving what it did for you. This is valid.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What Were You Really Searching For?</h3>
        <p>What did your addiction provide? Comfort? Escape? Numbness? Identity? A social world? Naming this without shame is the first step. The need underneath was real — even if the solution was harmful.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Healthy Replacements for the Same Needs</h3>
        <p>Recovery isn't about removing something — it's about finding safer ways to meet the same needs. Addiction provided escape → rest and safe recreation. Connection → peer support. The need doesn't go away; the path changes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"Your addiction is not you — but it feels like you, because you've spent so much intimate time together."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('grief')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="grief-losses">
      <p class="prompt">There are losses in recovery that don't get spoken aloud. Naming them reduces the pressure they create.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Processing Loss</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Common Losses Worth Naming</h3>
        <p>Loss of time and years. Loss of relationships. Loss of trust. Loss of opportunities (career, education). Loss of health. Loss of stability. Loss of identity clarity. Naming these is not self-pity — it's honesty that makes healing possible.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Grief Is Non-Linear</h3>
        <p>Grief comes in waves — sometimes gentle, sometimes overwhelming. Feeling okay for days then hitting a grief spike doesn't mean you're going backward. It means your nervous system is processing something significant.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What Strength Survived</h3>
        <p>Even in the middle of loss, something in you survived. Ask: "What qualities helped me make it this far?" Resilience, adaptability, hope, care for others — these are real, even when they're hard to see.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>A Gentle Writing Prompt</h3>
        <p>Write — just for you: "One thing I lost that I haven't talked about is ___. How this loss affects me now is ___. What I needed during that time was ___." Making it thinkable makes it more bearable.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('grief')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="grief-identity">
      <p class="prompt">Recovery is not about going back to who you were. It's about choosing who you are becoming.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Identity & Reconstruction</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Why Identity Gets Blurry</h3>
        <p>Addiction can blur a person's sense of self — disconnected from who you used to be, or losing sight of your values and direction. This is not failure. It's what happens when addiction affected the brain's stress, reward, and decision-making systems. It's context, not character.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Survival Identities vs Chosen Identities</h3>
        <p>Some identities formed to help you survive — "the strong one who doesn't need anything," "the angry one," "the reliable one who never asks for help." These were proof you became who you needed to be. Recovery gives you room to choose differently.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Values as Your Compass</h3>
        <p>When identity feels unclear, values still point forward. Even if you can't describe who you are yet, you may know what matters to you: honesty, stability, connection, health, growth. Values are directions, not achievements — you live into them one small action at a time.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Reconstruction Prompts</h3>
        <p>"One part of me I want to reconnect with is ___." "One part of me that survived despite everything is ___." "The identity I am rebuilding includes ___." You are not starting over — you are adding to your story with more intention.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"It's never too late to be what you might have been."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('grief')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="grief-selfcare">
      <p class="prompt">Grief is destabilizing. Self-care during grief is regulation — not indulgence.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Self-Care Through Grief</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Physical Care</h3>
        <p>Gentle movement. Regular meals, even small ones. Hydration. Intentional rest. Reducing sensory overload (noise, screens, clutter). Your body is working hard to process loss.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Emotional Care</h3>
        <p>Let emotions rise and fall without forcing or suppressing them. Use grounding practices when waves feel too big. Practice self-compassion — speak to yourself as you would to someone you love who is grieving.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Relational Care</h3>
        <p>Choose safe people. Set limits on what you can handle right now. Communicate honestly when you need space or presence. Grief can make us withdraw or over-rely — notice which direction you're pulled.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"Grief is not a sign that something is wrong — it is a sign that something mattered."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('grief')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SHAME -->
    <div class="passage" id="shame">
      <p class="prompt">Guilt and shame are not the same thing — and that difference matters a lot for recovery.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What feels closest to where you are?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('shame-guilt')">I feel guilty about specific things I've done</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('shame-shame')">I feel like I'm fundamentally broken or unworthy</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('shame-resentment')">I'm holding a lot of resentment toward someone or myself</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('shame-stigma')">I'm struggling with how others — or I — see people in recovery</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="shame-guilt">
      <p class="prompt">Guilt is about behaviour. When used constructively, it can actually guide you forward.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Working with Guilt</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Guilt vs Shame</h3>
        <p><strong>Guilt says:</strong> "I did something I don't feel good about." It's about behaviour. <strong>Shame says:</strong> "I am bad, broken, unworthy." It's about identity. Guilt can guide repair. Shame shuts people down and increases relapse risk.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Healthy Steps with Guilt</h3>
        <p>Acknowledge the feeling without spiraling. Take responsibility for what's actually yours. Repair when it's safe and appropriate. Commit to change through future actions. Seek support if guilt feels persistent or overwhelming.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Self-Compassion as Accountability</h3>
        <p>Accountability and self-compassion are not opposites. In fact, self-compassion is what makes accountability feel safe enough to stay with. "I can own my actions and still treat myself with respect."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"I can hold myself accountable without being cruel to myself."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('shame')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="shame-shame">
      <p class="prompt">Shame is not something you were born with. It was handed to you — and you don't have to keep carrying it.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Addressing Shame</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Where Shame Comes From</h3>
        <p>Shame grows in silence and isolation. It's often fuelled by stigma (others' judgments that became your inner voice), trauma, or messages from childhood and relationships. It is learned — which means it can be unlearned. It does not reflect the truth of who you are.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Physical Signs of Shame</h3>
        <p>Tight or heavy chest. Stomach discomfort. Avoiding eye contact. Heat in the face. Wanting to shrink or disappear. Racing heart. When you notice these — you may be in shame. Naming it helps.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Self-Compassion Practice — Three Steps</h3>
        <p><strong>Kindness:</strong> speak to yourself as you would to someone you care about who is struggling. <strong>Common humanity:</strong> struggle is part of being human, not proof of defect. <strong>Mindfulness:</strong> notice the shame feeling without over-identifying with it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Truths to Return To</h3>
        <p>Struggling is not a moral failure. Addiction is a health concern, not a character flaw. Recovery is resilience. Your past is not your identity. You are not your worst moments. Asking for help is strength.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('shame')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="shame-resentment">
      <p class="prompt">Resentment is often a shield for pain — and it costs more than it protects.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Working with Resentment</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What Resentment Protects</h3>
        <p>Resentment often protects us from being hurt again, from being vulnerable, or from feeling the primary emotions underneath — hurt, fear, grief. This is survival logic. You don't have to let go yet — but understanding it loosens its grip.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Exploring Safely</h3>
        <p>Ask: "What does this resentment help me avoid feeling?" "What emotion is underneath it?" "What need is not being met?" You're not required to forgive or reconcile. You're just looking at what the resentment is protecting.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Forgiveness: For Your Peace</h3>
        <p>Forgiveness (if and when it comes) is an internal choice to release resentment — not excusing the harm, not trusting the person again, not reconnecting. It's about your inner freedom. The other person doesn't have to be part of the process.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>A Small Letting-Go Ritual</h3>
        <p>Write the resentment on paper and fold it shut. Take a slow breath out and imagine the weight leaving your body. Close your eyes and say: "I'm setting this down for now." Even small rituals can shift something internally.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"I don't have to let go yet to understand what hurts."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('shame')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="shame-stigma">
      <p class="prompt">Stigma doesn't come from truth. It comes from fear and misunderstanding — and it doesn't belong to you.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Understanding & Challenging Stigma</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>The Three Types of Stigma</h3>
        <p><strong>Public stigma:</strong> stereotypes and judgment from society. <strong>Structural stigma:</strong> barriers built into systems (housing, healthcare, employment). <strong>Internalized stigma:</strong> when outside messages become your inner voice. Internalized stigma is often the most painful — because it feels like it's coming from you.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Truth vs Stigma</h3>
        <p>Stigma says "addiction is a choice." Truth: it's a treatable health condition. Stigma says "people like me don't change." Truth: recovery is happening every day. Stigma was handed to you. You don't have to hand it back to yourself.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Reclaiming Your Story</h3>
        <p>Your past is not your identity. You are not your worst moments. You deserve support, dignity, and safety — at every stage of recovery. Healing these internalized beliefs is how shame loses its power.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('shame')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- RELATIONSHIPS -->
    <div class="passage" id="relationships">
      <p class="prompt">Communication and connection are learnable skills — even when recovery has made them feel harder.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What's closest to what you're navigating?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('rel-assertive')">I struggle to say what I need or set boundaries</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('rel-conflict')">I'm in conflict or things escalated and I need help de-escalating</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('rel-trust')">Trust feels broken — with someone else or with myself</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('rel-listen')">I want to communicate better — listen, empathize, connect</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="rel-assertive">
      <p class="prompt">Assertiveness says: "Both of us matter." It's the middle ground between passive, aggressive, and passive-aggressive.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Assertive Communication</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>DEAR MAN — A Step-by-Step Script</h3>
        <p><strong>D</strong>escribe the facts. <strong>E</strong>xpress your feeling. <strong>A</strong>ssert your need or boundary. <strong>R</strong>einforce why it matters. <strong>M</strong>indful — stay on point. <strong>A</strong>ppear confident (calm tone, upright posture). <strong>N</strong>egotiate if it makes sense.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>"I" Statements</h3>
        <p>Formula: "I feel ___ when ___ because ___. What I need is ___." Example: "I feel frustrated when plans change suddenly because I need stability. I need more notice." No blame — just your experience and need.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Saying "No" Clearly</h3>
        <p>"I can't do that." "That doesn't work for me." "I'm not comfortable with that." You don't need to explain. Notice the urge to over-justify and ask: "Do I need to say more, or is this enough?"</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Assertive Beliefs to Build</h3>
        <p>"My feelings and needs are important." "It's okay to say no without feeling guilty." "I can be direct and still be kind." "Boundaries protect my recovery — they're not mean or selfish."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('relationships')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="rel-conflict">
      <p class="prompt">Conflict doesn't mean something is wrong with you or the relationship. How you handle it is what matters.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">De-escalation & Conflict Skills</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Catch It Early — Signs of Escalation</h3>
        <p><strong>Body:</strong> tight jaw, faster heartbeat, shoulders rising. <strong>Communication:</strong> interrupting, sarcasm, bringing up the past. <strong>Internal:</strong> "I need to win this" or "I need to escape." The earlier you notice, the more control you keep.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>De-escalation Tools</h3>
        <p><strong>Pause:</strong> one slow breath before responding. <strong>Ground:</strong> feel your feet, relax your shoulders. <strong>Wise Mind check:</strong> "What matters most right now?" <strong>Clarify:</strong> "Can you help me understand what you meant?" <strong>Take space:</strong> "I want to finish this conversation, but I need a short break."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Conflict Styles — Know Yours</h3>
        <p><strong>Avoidant:</strong> pulls away, shuts down. <strong>Aggressive:</strong> pushes, dominates. <strong>Passive-aggressive:</strong> indirect, sarcasm. <strong>Collaborative:</strong> listens, stays calm, solves together. All styles except collaborative are survival habits. They can be changed with practice.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Ending a Hard Conversation</h3>
        <p>"I need a minute. Let's talk again later." "I want to keep this healthy, so I'm taking a break." "I care about you and I don't want this to become an argument." You have the right to protect your peace.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('relationships')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="rel-trust">
      <p class="prompt">Trust is not a moral issue. Broken trust is an injury — and injuries can heal. Slowly, through small repeated actions.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Rebuilding Trust</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Self-Trust First</h3>
        <p>Self-trust grows through tiny promises you keep to yourself. Not big vows — just small, doable commitments: drink one glass of water, show up to one appointment, take three breaths before reacting. Each one builds evidence that you can rely on yourself.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Green and Red Flags in Others</h3>
        <p>Trust is built by: consistency, honesty, reliability, following through, apologizing and repairing. Trust is damaged by: excuses without changed behaviour, inconsistency, dishonesty. Apologies only matter when followed by changed behaviour.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The Circle of Trust</h3>
        <p>Not everyone deserves access to all of you. Some people belong in your inner circle (deep trust), some in the middle ring (some trust), some in the outer ring (guarded or building). You get to decide — and it can change over time.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Repairing Ruptures</h3>
        <p>Name the harm. Take ownership — no excuses, no blame. Share your plan. Check in on what the other person needs. Give space. Stay consistent over time. Repair is a process, not a single moment.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('relationships')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="rel-listen">
      <p class="prompt">Active listening is more than hearing words — it's being present with the person. This skill changes relationships.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Active Listening & Empathy</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The Four Steps of Active Listening</h3>
        <p><strong>1. Pay Attention:</strong> no phone, no rehearsing your response. <strong>2. Reflect:</strong> "What I heard you say was…" / "It sounds like you're feeling…" <strong>3. Clarify:</strong> "Can you tell me more?" <strong>4. Respond:</strong> after they finish — not before.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Validation — What It Is</h3>
        <p>Validation means: "Your feelings make sense." Not: agreeing, approving of behaviour, or fixing the problem. "It makes sense that you'd feel that way given what happened" is enough. When people feel heard, their nervous system settles.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Empathy vs Advice</h3>
        <p><strong>Advice:</strong> jumps to solutions — often shuts down sharing. <strong>Empathy:</strong> "I'm here with you in those feelings" — builds connection and safety. You don't need perfect words. You need presence.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Validation Phrases</h3>
        <p>"It makes sense that you feel…" / "I hear that this was really hard." / "Anyone in your situation might feel…" / "That sounds really important to you." Simple and effective.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('relationships')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CURIOUS -->
    <div class="passage" id="curious">
      <p class="prompt">Wanting to understand what's happening in your brain and body is one of the most useful instincts in recovery.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What are you most curious about?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('curious-brain')">What's actually happening as my brain heals</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('curious-cravings')">Why cravings happen and what to do with them</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('curious-emotions')">Why my emotions feel so big (or so absent) lately</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('curious-habits')">How habits and routines work — and how to build better ones</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('curious-values')">How to figure out what I actually value and want</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="curious-brain">
      <p class="prompt">Your brain is genuinely healing — and that process is more remarkable than most people realize.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Psychoeducation: Brain Healing</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Neuroplasticity: The Brain Can Change</h3>
        <p>The brain can form new connections, strengthen underused pathways, and prune old ones throughout your entire life. Recovery is literally neurological reconstruction. The brain you have today is not the same one you'll have in six months of sustained recovery.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>The Healing Timeline</h3>
        <p>Early recovery (days to weeks): acute withdrawal and initial recalibration. First few months: more stable but still changing brain chemistry. Meaningful recovery in dopamine systems often shows up at 3–12 months. The brain keeps improving well beyond that.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>What Accelerates Healing</h3>
        <p>Sleep, exercise, nutrition, and social connection are the four most evidence-supported inputs for neurological recovery. None of them are flashy — but each makes a measurable difference. The basics aren't boring — they're therapeutic.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Your Window of Tolerance</h3>
        <p>Everyone has a zone where they can think clearly and stay connected. When stress pushes you outside it, the body either speeds up (hyperarousal) or shuts down (hypoarousal). Breathing, grounding, and mindfulness help bring you back inside the window.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('curious')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="curious-cravings">
      <p class="prompt">Cravings make a lot more sense when you understand the machinery behind them.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Psychoeducation: Cravings</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Cue-Triggered Wanting</h3>
        <p>Your brain linked specific cues to substance use through repeated experience. Those cues now automatically activate a "wanting" signal — even if you don't consciously want to use. It's conditioning, not weakness.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Wanting vs Liking: Two Brain Systems</h3>
        <p>The wanting system gets overactive in addiction. The liking system becomes muted. That's why use stops feeling good long before the cravings stop. The urge to use doesn't mean it will feel good — it means the wanting system was activated.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Early Warning Signs of a Craving Building</h3>
        <p>Feeling foggy or disconnected. Irritability. Withdrawal from others. Rumination. Physical restlessness. These are early steps in the craving cycle. Noticing them earlier gives you more room to interrupt.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What Weakens the Pathway</h3>
        <p>Every time you ride out a craving without acting on it, you're weakening the cue-response link. The pathway genuinely does fade through repetition of new responses. This is neuroplasticity working for you.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('curious')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="curious-emotions">
      <p class="prompt">Emotional intensity — or the strange absence of emotion — is one of the most disorienting parts of early recovery.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Psychoeducation: Emotions in Recovery</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>The Prefrontal Cortex & Emotional Regulation</h3>
        <p>The prefrontal cortex regulates emotion, impulse, and judgment. Prolonged substance use affects it. As it heals, emotions can swing widely or feel muted — both are part of the same recalibration. It gets more stable with time and skill-building.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Emotions Come in Waves</h3>
        <p>Emotions are not permanent states. They rise, peak, and fall. Even strong emotions usually peak and pass within minutes when not fought or avoided. Riding the wave — staying present without escaping — is how emotions move through instead of getting stuck.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>The Functions of Emotions</h3>
        <p>Emotions motivate action. They communicate to others. They communicate to ourselves — like an internal alarm system. They are signals, not problems. Learning to read your emotional signals is one of the most valuable recovery skills.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('curious')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="curious-habits">
      <p class="prompt">Habits aren't personality traits. They're learned patterns — and new ones are built the same way old ones were.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Psychoeducation: Habits & Routine</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>The Habit Loop: Cue → Action → Reward</h3>
        <p>Your brain learns what's repeated. Every habit follows this loop. The brain releases dopamine at the reward stage, signalling "remember this." Over time, the cue triggers the action automatically. This is how recovery habits form too.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Replacing, Not Erasing</h3>
        <p>Habits are rarely erased — they're replaced. The cue stays the same; the response changes. Old habit: stress → substance use → relief. New habit: stress → grounding → calmer body. Same cue, different path, meaningful reward.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Habit Stacking</h3>
        <p>Pair a new habit with something you already do: "After I brush my teeth → I take three slow breaths." "After breakfast → I check in with my mood." Attaching new behaviours to existing anchors reduces reliance on motivation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Why Routines Matter</h3>
        <p>The brain prefers predictability. Trauma and addiction disrupt routine — which increases emotional volatility and relapse risk. Even 2–3 daily anchors tell your nervous system: "It's safe." Structure is not punishment — it's protection.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('curious')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="curious-values">
      <p class="prompt">Values are the qualities that guide how you want to live — not goals, not rules, but ongoing directions you live into.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Exploring Values & Direction</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What Values Are (and Aren't)</h3>
        <p>Values are not achievements — they're directions. "Be honest" is a value. "Tell the truth in this conversation" is a goal connected to that value. Values continue even when you miss a goal. They're how you want to show up, not a score you receive.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Common Values to Explore</h3>
        <p>Honesty · Courage · Compassion · Steadiness · Connection · Health · Responsibility · Growth · Respect · Boundaries · Creativity · Community · Self-respect · Hope · Balance · Patience. Circle any that resonate — even if you're not living them yet.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Values → Small Actions</h3>
        <p>Values become real through consistent small actions. Value: compassion → action: take one breath before responding. Value: health → action: drink water. Value: growth → action: try one new small thing. The action doesn't have to be big.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Your Personal Mission Statement</h3>
        <p>Try completing: "I want to live with ___, ___, and ___, and show up in ways that reflect ___ and ___." Make it honest, realistic, and steady — not perfect. Something you could say on a hard day and still believe.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('curious')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SUPPORT -->
    <div class="passage" id="support">
      <p class="prompt">Wanting to talk to someone is a sign of self-awareness, not weakness.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What feels most like what you're looking for?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('support-crisis')">I need to talk to someone urgently — I'm not doing okay</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('support-peer')">I want to connect with people who've been through this</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('support-professional')">I want to see a counsellor or care provider</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('support-someone')">I just need to reach one safe person in my life</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="support-crisis">
      <p class="prompt">Please reach out right now. You don't need to be in the worst moment of your life to deserve immediate support.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Crisis Resources</p>
      <div class="tool-card crisis-card">
        <h3>988 — Call or Text</h3>
        <p>Available 24/7. For mental health crises, substance use crises, or if you're not sure. A real person answers.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card crisis-card">
        <h3>Crisis Text Line</h3>
        <p>Text <strong>HOME to 741741</strong>. If talking out loud feels like too much right now.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card crisis-card">
        <h3>ConnexOntario</h3>
        <p>Call <strong>1-866-531-2600</strong> — 24/7 access to mental health and addiction support across Ontario.</p>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('support')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="support-peer">
      <p class="prompt">Peer connection is one of the most powerful things in recovery. Being around people who truly get it changes something.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>AA / NA Meetings</h3>
        <p>In-person and online meetings available daily in most communities. <strong>aa.org</strong> or <strong>na.org</strong> to find local listings.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>SMART Recovery</h3>
        <p>Science-based peer support — no higher-power framework required. Online and in-person. <strong>smartrecovery.org</strong></p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Your Program's Peer Network</h3>
        <p>If you've been through a residential or outpatient program, ask about their peer support or alumni community. These connections tend to be strong because you share context.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
