    <div class="passage" id="sc-physical">
      <p class="prompt">Physical self-care directly supports the nervous system — and the nervous system supports everything else.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Physical Self-Care</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Sleep — The Highest-Leverage Tool</h3>
        <p>Sleep disruption is one of the most underestimated relapse risk factors. Start with consistent wake times (more important than bedtime). Limit screens an hour before bed. Avoid caffeine after 2pm. If sleep remains disrupted, raise it with your care team.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The 3×3 Movement Rule</h3>
        <p>Move for 3 minutes, 3 times per day. A short walk, gentle stretching, standing and shifting weight. Consistent gentle movement reduces cravings, improves mood, and supports sleep. You don't need a gym — you need repetition.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Nutrition in Recovery</h3>
        <p>Eating something is more supportive than waiting to eat "perfectly." Aim for protein + carbohydrate + fat + vegetables when possible. Regular meals help stabilize blood sugar, mood, and craving intensity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Hydration</h3>
        <p>Even mild dehydration affects mood, focus, and emotional regulation. Drink water regularly. It's one of the smallest and most impactful actions you can take.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('selfcare')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="sc-emotional">
      <p class="prompt">Emotional self-care is about allowing feelings to exist and move through — not fixing or suppressing them.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Emotional Self-Care</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Quick Emotional Check-In</h3>
        <p>Right now: What do you notice in your body? What feeling is present? Where do you feel it most? What triggered it? What does this emotion need (comfort, space, clarity, connection, rest)? What would help you regulate?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Self-Compassion Statements</h3>
        <p>"This is hard, and I'm doing my best right now." "My feelings make sense. I'm allowed to have them." "I don't have to solve this all today." Choose one that fits and return to it when things get heavy.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Early Warning Signs — Notice Them</h3>
        <p>Pulling away from people. Skipping meals. Sleeping poorly. Irritability or numbness. Avoiding appointments. Looping thoughts. Feeling overwhelmed by small things. These signs mean you need more support — not less.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Affirmations That Actually Work</h3>
        <p>Choose statements true enough to say on a hard day: "I can pause before I react." "This feeling will pass." "I don't have to have everything figured out right now." "I am learning at my own pace." Small and honest beats big and hollow.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('selfcare')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="sc-meaning">
      <p class="prompt">When meaning disappears, recovery can feel like white-knuckling. Reconnecting to what matters changes that.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Meaning, Purpose & Values</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What Actually Matters to You</h3>
        <p>Values are not what you're supposed to care about — they're what actually moves you. Think of a moment recently when something felt important to protect or honour. That's probably a value. Start there.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Values → One Small Action Today</h3>
        <p>Pick one value. Ask: "What is the smallest action I could take today that lives in that direction?" Not a life change — just a step. Value: honesty → action: name how you actually feel to one person. That's it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Your 3-Month Direction</h3>
        <p>Recovery grows when you're moving toward something, not just away from substances. Ask: "Over the next 90 days, what do I want my life to feel like?" Not to look like — to feel like. Let that answer pull you forward.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Contribution as a Recovery Tool</h3>
        <p>One of the fastest ways to feel meaningful is to be useful to someone else. Volunteer. Check in on a peer. Share what you've learned. Contribution isn't just generosity — it's a recovery tool.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('selfcare')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="sc-fun">
      <p class="prompt">Fun is not a luxury in recovery — it's neurological medicine. It rewires your brain toward life, not substances.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Rebuilding Pleasure & Joy</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Why Things Don't Feel Enjoyable Right Now</h3>
        <p>Substances created large dopamine surges. Over time, the brain produces less dopamine naturally and everyday activities feel flat. This is not permanent — it's neurological recovery. Doing enjoyable things even when they don't feel enjoyable yet helps the brain slowly relearn pleasure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Types of Fun to Try</h3>
        <p><strong>Quiet:</strong> reading, puzzles, music, journaling. <strong>Active:</strong> walking, stretching, dancing. <strong>Creative:</strong> cooking, writing, drawing. <strong>Social:</strong> calls, group activities. <strong>Comfort:</strong> warm bath, favourite snack, cozy blankets. Start wherever the barrier feels lowest.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The 5-Minute Rule</h3>
        <p>Do it for just 5 minutes. Stop before you're tired. You're not trying to feel great — you're showing your brain that non-substance activities can produce something. Consistency matters more than enjoyment in early recovery.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Hobbies Rebuild Identity</h3>
        <p>Addiction can shrink who you are down to survival. Hobbies remind you who you are beyond that — what you're curious about, what you're capable of. Even a small hobby reconnects you to yourself.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"Fun rewires your brain toward life. Even small, enjoyable moments are meaningful and therapeutic."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('selfcare')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- RELAPSE -->
    <div class="passage" id="relapse">
      <p class="prompt">Relapse is not the end of your recovery. It's a moment in a longer process — and this moment can be turned around.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What's closest to where you are right now?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('relapse-early')">I'm noticing warning signs — I haven't used but I'm worried</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('relapse-happened')">It happened — I slipped and I need to get back on track</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('relapse-understand')">I want to understand how relapse works so I can prevent it</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('relapse-plan')">I want to build a real prevention plan</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="relapse-early">
      <p class="prompt">Noticing early warning signs is one of the most protective things you can do. You're already ahead of it.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Early Warning Signs & Intervention</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Common Early Warning Signs</h3>
        <p><strong>Emotional:</strong> irritability, loneliness, numbness, hopelessness. <strong>Cognitive:</strong> "I don't need help," "one time won't hurt," "I've got this alone." <strong>Behavioural:</strong> skipping self-care, isolating, avoiding supports. <strong>Physical:</strong> fatigue, craving spikes, sleep problems.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Interrupt the Chain Now</h3>
        <p>The relapse chain is: Trigger → Thought → Feeling → Urge → Action. You're in the early stages. Interrupt with: grounding, one slow breath, naming what you feel, reaching out to one person, or changing your environment.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The STOP Skill</h3>
        <p><strong>S</strong> — Stop. <strong>T</strong> — Take a breath. <strong>O</strong> — Observe (what am I feeling? what's happening?). <strong>P</strong> — Proceed mindfully. Choose your next step with care — not impulse.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Tell Someone Before It Gets Harder</h3>
        <p>Tell someone you trust what you're noticing. You don't need the situation to be a crisis to deserve support. "I'm noticing some warning signs" is enough to say.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('relapse')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="relapse-happened">
      <p class="prompt">A lapse is a moment — not the end of your recovery story. Your progress is not erased. Here's how to come back.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Rebuilding After a Slip</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Lapse vs Relapse — An Important Distinction</h3>
        <p><strong>A lapse</strong> is a single slip. It doesn't erase progress. It's a warning light, not an engine failure. <strong>A relapse</strong> happens when a lapse becomes a pattern — pulling away from support, stopping routines, sliding into old habits. Both are recoverable. Both are interruptible.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Interrupt the Shame Spiral Now</h3>
        <p>The most dangerous part of a slip is the shame spiral after: Slip → Shame → Hiding → Isolation → More urges → More use. Shame says "hide it." Recovery says "name it." Break the spiral by telling one safe person what happened.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Steps to Rebuild</h3>
        <ul class="steps">
          <li>Pause and breathe — don't react yet</li>
          <li>Name what happened without judgment: "I had a slip because something felt too big."</li>
          <li>Reach out to one safe person</li>
          <li>Use one grounding skill</li>
          <li>Return to one small routine (eat, drink water, step outside)</li>
          <li>Learn from the moment without punishing yourself</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card crisis-card">
        <h3>If You Need Help Right Now</h3>
        <p>ConnexOntario: <strong>1-866-531-2600</strong> (24/7) · Crisis line: call or text <strong>988</strong> · Crisis Text: <strong>HOME to 741741</strong></p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"A lapse is just a step on the road, not the end of the journey. What matters is getting back on track."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('relapse')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="relapse-understand">
      <p class="prompt">Understanding how relapse works is itself a prevention tool.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Psychoeducation: Relapse Prevention</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Relapse Is a Process, Not a Moment</h3>
        <p>Relapse usually builds over time through stress, thoughts, emotions, and old habits. The pattern: Trigger → Thought → Feeling → Urge → Action → Consequence → Emotion → Re-trigger. Recognizing the chain gives you control and reduces shame.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Risk Factors vs Protective Factors</h3>
        <p><strong>Risk factors</strong> (what makes slips more likely): loneliness, stress, no routine, exhaustion, shame spirals, certain people or places, all-or-nothing thinking. <strong>Protective factors</strong> (what keeps you steady): coping skills, values, routines, supportive people, emotional awareness, self-compassion.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Shame Fuels Relapse</h3>
        <p>Shame says "hide it." It pulls you away from the support that would actually help. Self-compassion interrupts this cycle — not by excusing the behaviour, but by making it safe enough to stay connected to support.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What Resilience Actually Means</h3>
        <p>Resilience is not never struggling. It's the ability to notice, adjust, and return. Each time you recover faster, pause sooner, or don't make things worse — that's resilience building.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('relapse')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="relapse-plan">
      <p class="prompt">A real relapse prevention plan — built before you need it — changes everything.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Building Your Prevention Plan</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Know Your Triggers</h3>
        <p><strong>Internal:</strong> stress, loneliness, frustration, exhaustion, physical pain. <strong>External:</strong> certain people, places, objects, times of day, conflict. Write yours down somewhere you can access them.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Build Your Coping Menu</h3>
        <p>Before a high-risk moment: choose 3–5 tools across categories. <strong>Body:</strong> breathing, grounding, cold water, movement. <strong>Mind:</strong> thought defusion, STOP skill, Wise Mind. <strong>Heart:</strong> calling someone, journaling, self-compassion. Having options means you can switch when one isn't working.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Your Support Map</h3>
        <p>Name 2–3 people you can contact when cravings are high. Decide now. What's the first thing you'd say? Even "I'm having a hard moment" is enough. If no one comes to mind — ConnexOntario: <strong>1-866-531-2600</strong></p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>If I Slip — My Safety Plan</h3>
        <p>Decide in advance: What's the first thing I'll do? Who will I reach out to? What grounding skill will I use? What one routine can I return to? A plan made before a crisis is far more effective than one made in the middle of one.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"Recovery is not about avoiding every challenge perfectly. It's about building a life where your choices and supports help you stay strong."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('relapse')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- VULNERABILITY -->
    <div class="passage" id="vulnerability">
      <p class="prompt">Wanting to open up but feeling unsafe about it — that's not weakness. It's often the most honest place to start.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What feels closest to where you're at?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('vuln-what')">I don't really understand what vulnerability is or why it matters</button>
