    <div class="passage" id="vuln-what">
      <p class="prompt">Vulnerability is one of the most misunderstood words in recovery. Let's clear it up.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Understanding Vulnerability</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>What Vulnerability Actually Is</h3>
        <p>Vulnerability means being honest and open about your feelings, needs, and experiences — in a way that is safe, intentional, and within your control. It is showing up as your real self, without pretending or numbing, while still protecting your boundaries. It is courageous, not weak.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>What Vulnerability Is NOT</h3>
        <p>Oversharing everything with everyone. Being fragile or "too emotional." Putting yourself in unsafe situations. Letting people cross your limits. Losing control of what you share. You always get to decide what, when, and with whom you share.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Why It Matters in Recovery</h3>
        <p>In addiction, many people learn to hide pain, needs, and fear to survive. Vulnerability reverses that pattern. It helps you: share real feelings instead of bottling them up, ask for help before things escalate, build trust with safe people, and reduce shame — because shame grows in silence.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>How Addiction Blocks It</h3>
        <p>Substances are often used to avoid or numb emotions instead of expressing them. This makes vulnerability difficult: feelings become harder to identify, shame makes honesty feel dangerous, and isolation reduces the chances for real connection. Recovery is slowly rebuilding the ability to feel, name, and share safely.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"Vulnerability is choosing honesty with boundaries."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('vulnerability')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="vuln-armour">
      <p class="prompt">The armour you built made sense. It kept you safe. Understanding it is the first step to choosing when to take it off.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Understanding Your Protective Patterns</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Common Forms of Armour</h3>
        <p>These are protective strategies that once helped you survive — and now may limit connection: <strong>Humour</strong> (deflecting with jokes), <strong>Perfectionism</strong> (nothing can hurt what's already perfect), <strong>Shutting down</strong>, <strong>Anger</strong> (pushing people away before they can leave), <strong>Sarcasm</strong>, <strong>People-pleasing</strong> (making everyone else okay so you don't have to be seen), <strong>Over-explaining</strong>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What Armour Protects</h3>
        <p>Every form of armour is protecting something real: fear of rejection, fear of being seen as broken, fear of being hurt again, not wanting to disappoint. The protection made sense. The question now is whether the cost — loneliness, disconnection, hiding — is still worth it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Hyperindependence as Armour</h3>
        <p>"I only rely on myself" often started as a survival strategy — if you don't need anyone, no one can let you down. In recovery, this pattern can look like refusing help, dismissing support, or pushing people away when things get close. It's protective logic that can become isolating.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>A Gentle Question to Sit With</h3>
        <p>"Which armour do I reach for most?" Naming it — without judgment — creates the first bit of space between you and the automatic response.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('vulnerability')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="vuln-practice">
      <p class="prompt">Practicing vulnerability doesn't mean opening everything at once. It means taking one small, safe step.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Practicing Vulnerability Safely</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Check If It's Safe First</h3>
        <p>Before sharing something vulnerable, ask: Does this person respect me? Do they listen? Do they keep things private? Do they share honestly too? Do I feel calmer after talking with them? If several of these feel uncertain — start smaller, or choose a different person.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Start Small</h3>
        <p>Vulnerability builds in layers. You don't need to share everything. A starter sentence: <strong>"I feel ___ when ___."</strong> That's it. One honest sentence to one safe person is a real act of vulnerability. The next step gets easier.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Expect Some Nerves — That's Normal</h3>
        <p>Feeling nervous when practicing vulnerability doesn't mean you're doing it wrong. It means it matters. Helpful reminders: I can go slow. I don't have to share everything. I can stop at any time. Feeling nervous is not a sign of danger.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Choose the Right Place</h3>
        <p>A quiet room, a walk, with a staff member, with a trusted peer. You never owe vulnerability to a space or person that feels unsafe. Safety first — then honesty.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"You don't have to share everything to be seen. One honest sentence is enough to start."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('vulnerability')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="vuln-forgiveness">
      <p class="prompt">Forgiveness is one of the most misunderstood words in recovery. Let's start with what it actually means.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Forgiveness, Reconciliation & Letting Go</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Three Different Things</h3>
        <p><strong>Forgiveness</strong> — an internal process where you release resentment and shift toward understanding or compassion. This happens inside you, even if the other person never apologizes. <strong>Reconciliation</strong> — rebuilding a relationship together, which requires two people and trust. <strong>Letting go</strong> — a neutral emotional release, like loosening your grip on anger or pain. Forgiveness and reconciliation are not the same. You can forgive without reconnecting.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>What Forgiveness Is NOT</h3>
        <p>Excusing the harm. Forgetting what happened. Pretending it didn't matter. Automatically trusting the person again. Returning to the relationship. Letting someone hurt you again. Forgiveness is about your inner freedom — not supporting the other person's behaviour. <em>Note: forgiveness is never expected for trauma or abuse.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Why Forgiveness Helps You</h3>
        <p>Research shows forgiveness lowers stress, reduces anger, improves emotional wellbeing, and increases self-respect and peace of mind. The other person doesn't have to apologize, change, or even be part of the process. You do it for yourself.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>A Small Letting-Go Ritual</h3>
        <p>You don't have to be ready to forgive to try letting go of a little weight. Write the resentment or pain on paper and fold it shut. Take a slow breath out and imagine the weight leaving your body. Say quietly: "I'm setting this down for now." This is for your peace — not a verdict on what happened.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Self-Forgiveness</h3>
        <p>Many people in recovery find forgiving themselves harder than forgiving others. Self-forgiveness is not excusing what happened — it's choosing to stop punishing yourself for something you're already working to change. "I can own my actions and still treat myself with respect."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"Forgiveness is about my peace, not their behaviour."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('vulnerability')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- MOTIVATION -->
    <div class="passage" id="motivation">
      <p class="prompt">Losing momentum in recovery is common and doesn't mean you've failed. Let's find what's still true for you.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What feels closest to where you are?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('motivation-why')">I've lost track of why recovery matters to me</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('motivation-can')">I'm not sure I'm actually capable of doing this</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('motivation-pillars')">I want to understand what a healthy recovery actually looks like</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('motivation-affirmations')">I need something to hold onto — a phrase, a reminder, something true</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="motivation-why">
      <p class="prompt">Your "why" is the engine of recovery. When it gets buried under stress and exhaustion, it's worth digging back to.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Motivational Interviewing: Reason & Need</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Your Reason — Why Change Matters</h3>
        <p>A reason is the <em>why</em> behind recovery. It might be: wanting better health, wanting a calmer life, wanting to feel proud of yourself, wanting to rebuild trust, wanting peace. It sounds like: "I want this because…" or "This matters to me because…" Write or say one reason out loud right now — even if it feels small.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Your Need — What a Better Life Requires</h3>
        <p>A need is what helps you feel stable, safe, and supported. It might be: structure, connection, rest, honesty, purpose, healthy coping. It sounds like: "I need this in my life…" or "My future self needs me to…" Needs are not weaknesses — they are foundations.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Reason + Need = Motivation</h3>
        <p>When you combine <em>why you want recovery</em> with <em>what you need to feel steady</em>, motivation strengthens. Example: "I want peace + I need structure = I want to build routines that help me feel calm." Try your own version.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Values as Your Compass</h3>
        <p>Values guide choices and give recovery meaning. Ask: "What matters most to me?" "When I picture my future, what do I hope for?" "What value do I want to live by?" Even if identity feels blurry, values still point forward.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"Motivation is what gets you started. Habit is what keeps you going."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('motivation')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="motivation-can">
      <p class="prompt">Doubting your ability is one of the most common — and most painful — parts of recovery. Let's look at what you've actually already done.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Motivational Interviewing: Ability & Desire</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Your Ability — Evidence You Already Have</h3>
        <p>Ability means noticing the skills, strengths, and experiences that prove you are capable of change. Think of moments when you overcame something difficult, made progress, kept going when things were hard, or surprised yourself with strength. Ability is not about perfection — it's about remembering what you're made of.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Times You've Handled Hard Things</h3>
        <p>You have changed difficult things before — even if it doesn't feel that way right now. Ask: "One time I changed something difficult was ___. What helped me succeed? What does that show about what I'm capable of?" Look at that evidence honestly.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Your Desire — What You Actually Want</h3>
        <p>Desire connects recovery to meaning. It sounds like: "I want more peace." "I want to feel proud of myself." "I want better relationships." "I want to stay alive and present." What do you want? Not what you're supposed to want — what you actually want?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>One Small Commitment</h3>
        <p>Commitment doesn't mean doing everything perfectly. It means taking one small step toward the life you want. What's one thing you can do in the next 24 hours to support your recovery? Something small enough to actually do.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"You are the author of your own life. Today is a chance to write a new page."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('motivation')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="motivation-pillars">
      <p class="prompt">Recovery is more than abstinence. Here's what a whole healthy recovery actually looks like.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">The 8 Pillars of Healthy Recovery</p>
      <div class="tool-card info-card">
        <h3>Recovery as a Lifestyle</h3>
        <p>Recovery is not just stopping substance use. It's building a whole life — how you sleep, who you spend time with, how you cope with stress, how you talk to yourself, how you make meaning, how you handle emotions and relationships. These eight pillars support long-term stability and wellbeing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The 8 Pillars</h3>
        <p><strong>1. Emotional Regulation</strong> — understanding emotions and responding instead of reacting.<br>
        <strong>2. Coping Skills</strong> — tools for stress, urges, and conflict.<br>
        <strong>3. Consistent Routines</strong> — daily structure (sleep, meals, basic care).<br>
        <strong>4. Physical Health</strong> — sleep, hydration, nutrition, movement, medical care.<br>
        <strong>5. Self-Compassion</strong> — how you speak to yourself when things get hard.<br>
        <strong>6. Healthy Community</strong> — people who support recovery rather than undermine it.<br>
        <strong>7. Values-Guided Action</strong> — doing what matters, not just what feels urgent.<br>
        <strong>8. Honest Communication</strong> — being honest with yourself and others.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>One Pillar at a Time</h3>
        <p>You don't need to work on all eight at once. Look at the list — which one feels most important right now? Which feels most depleted? Start there. Recovery grows one pillar at a time.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Redefining Success</h3>
        <p>Success in recovery isn't perfection. It's: showing up, noticing your feelings sooner, using skills when you can, reaching out instead of hiding, staying curious about yourself. Flexible progress counts. "Success is staying curious" is a valid definition.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"Recovery looks different for every person. You are not behind if your recovery looks different from someone else's."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('motivation')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="motivation-affirmations">
      <p class="prompt">The right words at the right moment can change your internal state. Here's how to find ones that actually work for you.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Affirmations That Work</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Why Most Affirmations Don't Work</h3>
        <p>Statements like "I love myself completely" or "Everything is perfect" can feel hollow or even increase shame when things are hard. Your brain rejects what it doesn't believe. Affirmations work when they feel true enough to say on a bad day — not just a good one.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Realistic Affirmations That Actually Help</h3>
        <p>"I can pause before I react." "This feeling will pass." "I can learn new skills." "I deserve support." "I can take one small step today." "I don't have to have everything figured out right now." "I am learning at my own pace." "It's okay to ask for help." Choose one that feels honest — not inspiring, just true.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Values-Based Affirmations</h3>
        <p>These feel most grounded because they connect to real action. Format: "My value of ___ shows up when I ___." Examples: "My value of honesty shows up when I say how I actually feel." "My value of health shows up when I take one small step today." "My value of connection shows up when I reach out instead of isolating."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>How to Use Them</h3>
        <p>Choose one statement. Say it slowly — out loud if possible. Don't force feeling. The point isn't to feel amazing immediately — it's to interrupt harsh self-talk and offer your brain a more accurate, kinder alternative. Repetition over time changes internal patterns.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>The Test</h3>
        <p>Ask: "Could I say this on a hard day?" If yes — it's a good affirmation for you. If it feels fake or adds pressure — make it smaller and more honest.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"I don't have to feel better to take a small step."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('motivation')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CONVERSATIONS -->
    <div class="passage" id="conversations">
      <p class="prompt">Coming back to the people in your life after treatment is one of the hardest parts of recovery. You don't need perfect words — just honest, steady ones.</p>
      <p class="sub-prompt">What kind of conversation feels hardest right now?</p>
      <div class="choices">
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('conv-private')">Someone is pushing me to share more than I'm ready to</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('conv-past')">Someone keeps bringing up my past</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('conv-stigma')">Someone is using language that hurts or feels stigmatizing</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('conv-support')">I want to ask for support but don't know how</button>
        <button class="choice" onclick="go('conv-end')">I need to end or step back from a hard conversation</button>
      </div>
      <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('start')">← Back</button>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="conv-private">
      <p class="prompt">You get to decide what you share and when. You don't owe anyone your full story.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Holding Your Boundaries Warmly</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Warm, Low-Disclosure Scripts</h3>
        <p>"I'm focusing on healing, and I'm keeping some things private right now." "Thanks for asking — I'm taking things one day at a time." "I appreciate your concern. I'm doing what I need to take care of myself." "I'm not ready to talk about the details, but I'm in a better place."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>When Someone Keeps Pushing</h3>
        <p>"I care about our relationship, so I want to talk about this slowly." "I'm still figuring things out. I'll share more when I'm ready." "I understand you're curious. For now, I'm keeping this part of my life between me and my supports."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>A Grounding Moment Before You Respond</h3>
        <p>Take one slow breath before responding. Ask yourself: "What matters most right now — connection, clarity, or calm?" That short pause lets you choose your words instead of reacting.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"I can speak kindly, clearly, and with self-respect. My story belongs to me."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('conversations')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="conv-past">
      <p class="prompt">People may bring up your past — sometimes awkwardly, sometimes harshly. Here's how to respond without losing ground.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Responding to the Past</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Warm and Honest</h3>
        <p>"Yeah, I went through some rough times. I'm working really hard to move forward." "I know I hurt people before. I'm trying to show change through my actions now." "I can't change what happened, but I'm focused on growing."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Warm and Boundaried</h3>
        <p>"I hear you. I'm working on myself, and I'd like to focus on the present." "I'm trying to rebuild trust step by step. I can keep showing up differently."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>When Someone Won't Let Go of Your Past</h3>
        <p>"I understand those memories are still there. I'm committed to doing better, and I hope we can slowly work toward something healthier." Warm does not mean self-blaming. Warm means grounded and honest — without shame.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>You Don't Have to Accept Ongoing Cruelty</h3>
        <p>There is a difference between someone working through hurt and someone weaponizing your past. If a person consistently uses your history to shame or control you, that is a boundary issue — not a conversation to keep having on their terms.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('conversations')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="conv-stigma">
      <p class="prompt">Language matters. You're allowed to name when a word or phrase doesn't fit where you're at.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Responding to Stigmatizing Language</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Gentle Correction</h3>
        <p>"It helps me when people use the word 'recovery' instead of 'addict.'" "I'm trying to think about this as a health issue, not a character flaw." "I know people mean well — language just makes a difference for me."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>More Direct — Still Warm</h3>
        <p>"I'm working hard on changing my life. It really helps when the words are supportive." This shifts the moment without creating conflict.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>A Note on the Word "Addict"</h3>
        <p>Some recovery communities (AA, NA) use this word as part of their tradition — as a way of reducing denial and creating shared honesty. Outside that setting, it can feel stigmatizing. Both are valid. You can respect that tradition and still choose different language for yourself. Terms like "person in recovery" may feel more accurate to where you are now.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>When It's Not Worth the Conversation</h3>
        <p>Not every person is ready to hear a correction. Sometimes protecting your energy means choosing not to engage. Walking away or changing the subject is a valid option.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('conversations')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="conv-support">
      <p class="prompt">Asking for support is one of the most important — and most uncomfortable — skills in recovery. People often want to help. They just need a map.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Asking for What You Need</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Warm Requests</h3>
        <p>"It would help me if you could check in once in a while." "It means a lot when people believe in me." "I'm trying to avoid old patterns. Could we do things differently this time?" "I'm focusing on staying grounded. Can we slow the conversation down?"</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>From a Place of Self-Respect</h3>
        <p>"I'm proud of the work I'm doing. I'd love your support as I keep going." You don't need to justify why you deserve support. You do.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Keeping It Simple</h3>
        <p>You don't need a long explanation. "I'm having a hard time and could use some company" is enough. "I need someone to talk to" is enough. Simple and direct is often more receivable than a full briefing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('conversations')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="passage" id="conv-end">
      <p class="prompt">Knowing when and how to step back from a conversation is a skill — not avoidance.</p>
      <hr class="divider">
      <p class="label">Ending or Pausing Hard Conversations</p>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Soft Exit Lines</h3>
        <p>"I think I need a minute. Let's talk again later." "I want to keep this conversation healthy, so I'm going to take a break." "I care about you and I don't want this to turn into an argument." "Thanks for listening — I need to pause here for today."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>When Emotions Are Rising</h3>
        <p>"I'm feeling overwhelmed. I need a few minutes to breathe and come back." "I'm not walking away from this — I just need a moment." Taking space is not the same as shutting down. You're choosing to come back regulated rather than reactive.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-card">
        <h3>Your Right to Protect Your Peace</h3>
        <p>You are allowed to end a conversation that is becoming harmful to you. Staying in a destructive exchange is not loyalty — it's risk. Stepping away cleanly and returning when calm is the more respectful option for both people.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="anchor-phrase">"I can protect my peace without abandoning the relationship."</div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <button class="restart-btn" onclick="go('start')">Start over</button>
        <button class="back-btn" onclick="go('conversations')">← Back</button>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div><!-- end card -->
</div><!-- end container -->

<script>
  function go(id) {
    const current = document.querySelector('.passage.active');
    const next = document.getElementById(id);
    if (!next) return;
    current.classList.remove('active');
    next.classList.add('active');
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
  }
</script>
